🌿 Part One
मूर्त और अमूर्त का रहस्य
Form and Formless
Background

In the previous Sarga, Sri Vasiṣṭha explained that Consciousness (Cit) alone is the ultimate Reality.

Now Sri Rama asks:

"If Consciousness is formless,
how can it possibly move this body,
which is solid and tangible?"

This is the same question modern philosophers ask:

"How does mind affect matter?"

Vedanta asks it even more profoundly:

"How does the Formless appear as the world of forms?"

Verse 1

Rama says there seem to be two kinds of things in the universe.

1. मूर्त (Mūrta)

Things that have measurable form.

They occupy space.

They collide with other objects.

Examples:

stone
body
tree
mountain
2. अमूर्त (Amūrta)

Things that have no measurable form.

Examples:

thought
memory
love
awareness
knowledge

These cannot be struck with a stick.

They have no weight.

Yet everyone knows they exist.

Here "formless" does not yet mean Brahman.

It simply means:

that which cannot physically collide.

This distinction is very important.

Verse 2

Sri Rama defines these terms more carefully.

सप्रतिघ

Things capable of physical collision.

अप्रतिघ

Things incapable of collision.

For example:

A wall stops your body.

But can a wall stop a thought?

Can your love collide with a mountain?

Can awareness bump into a stone?

No.

Therefore Consciousness belongs to the second category.

Verse 3

This is simply an observation.

Every day we see

stone strikes stone,

water strikes earth,

people strike doors.

But nobody has ever seen

knowledge strike a rock.

Awareness does not collide with matter.

Verse 4

Now comes a beautiful example.

Suppose you are looking at the moon.

What reaches the moon?

Certainly not your eyeball.

Nor your brain.

Yet your awareness immediately knows the moon.

There is no physical collision between your awareness and the moon.

Still,

the moon is experienced.

Sri Rama says:

How is this possible?

The Hidden Teaching

Already Vasiṣṭha is preparing us for something extraordinary.

Notice what Sri Rama unconsciously assumes.

He assumes

Consciousness and matter are two different realities.

That assumption itself will later be dissolved.

Because Vasiṣṭha will ultimately reveal:

Consciousness never actually "contacts" matter.

There is no second thing called matter independent of Consciousness.

Just as in a dream,

the dream body,

dream mountain,

dream river,

and dream sky

are all made of one mind,

likewise

the waking body,

the universe,

and every experience

are appearances in Consciousness alone.

Then the question,

"How does Consciousness touch matter?"

disappears,

because there are not two independent realities to be connected.

🌿 Practical Reflection

This teaching is not merely philosophical.

Every day we say:

"I am moving my hand."

Vedanta quietly asks:

Who is this "I"?

Is it the body?

The mind?

The intellect?

Or the silent Awareness in whose presence body, mind, and intellect appear to function?

The purpose of Sri Rama's questions is not to create doubt—it is to remove the deepest doubt of all: the assumption that Consciousness and matter are fundamentally separate.

🌸 Living Vedanta Library Takeaway

The problem exists only as long as we imagine two realities—Consciousness and matter.

Yoga Vāsiṣṭha gradually leads us to discover that there are not two.

The body appears in Consciousness; Consciousness does not enter the body.

When this is understood, the ancient puzzle of "How does the soul control the body?" dissolves naturally.
